Highlights
Large voracious slaughterhouses
threaten survival of small ones
It is no news to anyone that
meat sector companies just
keep on expanding their
operations both on the
domestic and international
markets. However, the news
that Marfrig (MRF) last week
acquired US group Keystone
Foods for US$1.26 billion
caused some disagreement
among market analysts.
Keystone is one of the largest
processed meat suppliers in the
world to fast food chains such
as McDonald's, Campbell's,
Subway, ConAgra, Yum
Brands, and Chipotle.
This puts Marfrig Alimentos on
the promising Chinese market
and opens up the possibility of
significant gains in its product
distribution in the Middle East. It
also makes the company the
third biggest in turnover among
meat processing companies,
after JBS, which is also
Brazilian, and Tyson Foods,
from the USA. With the
acquisition the group’s global
turnover will be US$15.4 billion.
In a teleconference with market
analysts and shareholders,
Marfrig’s CEO, Marcos Antonio
Molina dos Santos, said that
the purchase was what the
company needed to diversify its
products. “Keystone has stable
Ebitda, it doesn’t need any
working capital, it doesn’t need
remodeling, it will just boost
synergy", he said. This synergy
will total US$100 million, mainly
in Keystone’s distribution in
Europe, Asia, the Middle East
and the USA. Molina said
Keystone will distribute for
several Moy Park operations,
which Marfrig already owns in
Europe. "In the Middle East
sales are handled by importers,
and now Keystone will do the
distribution, as it will in Asia",
said Santos. Keystone, says
Marfrig, will generate excess
net cash of US$126 million,
which will finance investment in
China. Despite the billion-dollar
acquisition, announced on June
15th, the company’s stock price
fell 3.6% between Monday and
Friday, illustrating that market
analysts were not overly
confident.
The doubt involves Marfrig’s
ability to manage such a large
asset. To pay for the deal,
Marfrig is to launch R$2.5
billion in convertible
debentures, which after five
years will become stocks. The
company currently has about
347 million shares, and with this
deal it will get another 102
million. Uncertainty involves
how many investors will back
the debenture issue. Molina
said the names are clear. The
bet is that the name behind the
deal is the Brazilian State-
owned development bank,
BNDES, which has a 13.89%
stake in Marfrig and underwrote
the debentures for it to buy
Seara.
Continued on page2
June 18, 2010 Issue No.223
Online and in Print • Online Archive
Brazilian Meat Monitor, June 18, 2010 2 © 2010 Informa UK Ltd.
Both BNDES and Marfrig have refused to comment.
In addition, there is a doubt over the concentration of
the company’s revenue in one client. McDonald´s
accounts for 90% of Keystone’s revenue. Ricardo
Florence, Investor Relations director at Marfrig,
prefers not to comment on whether the revenue
streams will be diversified, but he did say, "The share
will continue to be strongly in favor of McDonald’s,
but we want to serve demand from our clients."
Molina added that the acquisition of Keystone Foods
is the last one for at least five years. This is the
period the company will have to raise the money for
the R$2.5 billion debenture issue. With Keystone,
Marfrig now has 151 units in 22 countries, and
85,000 employees. In the last three years alone the
company has bought 38 companies in Brazil and
elsewhere for over R$7 billion in total – one of the
most important being Seara, from Cargill, last year.
The flip side
Since 2007, when JBS-Friboi and Marfrig went
public, both companies have just kept on growing.
Back then, the profitability levels for beef processors
were exceptional, as animal prices were at record
lows. Also, that was when the global economy was
booming. This saw slaughterhouses owned by the
two giants stretch throughout Brazil and extend
internationally. One the one hand, these massive
mergers boosted the competitive standing of these
companies involved, as they were able to exploit
regional price differences and absorb intermediation
margins, increasing their distribution structures and
reducing fixed costs. However, small and medium-
sized slaughterhouses panicked.
The massive mergers caused a shortage of animals
as the big companies paid cash, which the smaller
ones could not match. The slaughterhouses had only
two choices left: either join the giants, or get into
niche markets. "These acquisitions are of great
concern for small and medium slaughterhouses
because they concentrate the segment, reducing
access to raw materials and slashing bargaining
power with wholesalers and retailers", says the
technical director at AgraFNP, José Vicente Ferraz.
In the harsh business climate, many small and
medium-sized slaughterhouses have had to close
down or file for bankruptcy protection. This is what
happened to Independência, Margen, Quatro Marcos
and Frialto. The massive mergers have threatened
the survival of the smaller businesses in Brazil..
BEEF Market Overview
This week the beef spot market fell, mainly because
of the limited supply of cattle for slaughter. It is
normal at this time of the year to have much higher
supply, because of the weather. Despite the lower
rates of slaughter at most plants, prices continued to
fall. Because of the lower volume of trade, prices did
not rise this week. The beef market in São Paulo,
which the week before had seen prices recover,
ended the week with prices down.

Brazilian Mercantile & Futures Exchange (BM&F)
BEEF Market
Between June 9th and 16th beef cattle futures due in
June/10 traded on the BM&FBovespa market rose.
On June 16th the price closed at R$82.22/@, up
0.16% on June 9th. The other contracts remained
steady.Traders say the steadiness during the week,
was down to limited supply, demand from
slaughterhouses and the World Cup. During the week
prices for June/10 fluctuated between R$81.78/@
and R$82.25/@.Up to June 16th the most liquid
contracts, due in July/10 and October/10, had 2,399
and 18,251 positions open, respectively, out of a total
of 59,091 contracts and options. The spreads
between June/10 and October/10 on June 16 fell by
1.93% on June 9th (R$2.57/@). However, the
contract to have appreciated most was October/10
over the week, limiting the spread’s fall, which was at
R$2.54/@ on the day.

BEEF News Summary
Marfrig to issue R$2.5 billion in
debentures
To finance its acquisition of US company Keystone
Foods, Marfrig Alimentos is to issue R$2.5 billion
(about US$1.3 billion) in five-year convertible
debentures. Current shareholders will have
preference at a price of R$21.50 per share.The CEO
of Marfrig, Marcos Molina, told Valor that instead of
acquiring slaughterhouses the company preferred to
invest in added-value product development by paying
US$1.26 billion for a company which is one of the
world’s largest suppliers of processed meats to
McDonald's, Campbell's, Subway, ConAgra, Yum
Brands and Chipotle, with net revenue of US$6.4
billion in 2009.
With Keystone, Marfrig will gain a presence in 22
countries and revenue of R$28 billion, compared with
R$10.28 billion last year. In the last three years
Marfrig has bought 38 companies in Brazil and
abroad, spending over R$7 billion. One of the major
acquisitions was Seara, from Cargill, last year. Now
the challenge to integrate all these companies is
even greater. Information provided by Valor.
Frialto to resume slaughter in Mato
Grosso State
The Frialto group is to resume cattle slaughter at its
Matupá plant (Mato Grosso State) on June 16th. The
plant had been shut down last month when the group
filed for bankruptcy protection. Slaughter will begin
with about 500 employees, out of the 700 that used
to work at the plant. Its capacity is 800 head a day.
Information provided by Beefpoint.
Adapec: Russia releases beef
exports from Tocantins State
The municipalities of Paranã, Jaú do Tocantins and
Pedro Afonso in Tocantins State, Brazil, can now
export live cattle, genetic material and beef to Russia.
The decision to lift restrictions was announced on
June 16th by MAPA to the Cattle Farming Defense
Agency (Adapec). The municipalities had been
banned from exporting to Russia since September
22nd, October 20th and January 16th 2009,
respectively.
Following outbreaks of vesicular stomatitis, an
infectious cattle disease that can be passed to man.
On June 2nd 2009 the Russian government released
meat exports from the State, limiting the embargo to
the three municipalities were the diseases had been
focused. “Our work was fast and efficient in
controlling the outbreaks, complying with all the
sanitary recommendations made by the OIE”, said
José Luciano Azevedo, president of a Adapec.
Information provided by Beefpoint.
USA: Economy could hit demand
for meat
Uncertainty in the US economy could harm beef
producers. Improved cattle prices restored profits this
spring for farmers after at least two years of losses.
Wholesale prices for beef rose to close to their peaks
over the last two years in May as summer demand
peaked. Among the main meats demand for beef is
most sensitive to employment rates and household
income, says Assistant Professor of Agricultural
Economics at Kansas State University, Glynn Tonsor.
The growth in employment last month was lower than
expected and unemployment in the USA, at 9.7%, is
close to the highest it has been for 27 years. Last
month the USDA, in its monthly report on Supply and
Demand, cut its forecast for beef consumption in the
USA in 2010 to 26.89 kilos per person, from 27.07

kilos, 3.1% down on 2009 and the lowest per capita
consumption since 1952 according to USDA data.
Information provided by Drovers.
Beef production costs rise and
chicken benefits
Stricter environmental and sanitary standards will
increase beef production costs and slow expansion in
the next ten years, leading to increased chicken
consumption, say the FAO and OECD.
Global meat consumption will continue to rise at the
fastest rate among agricultural products. Virtually all
the increased demand will come from developing
countries, above all for chicken, which could rise by
2.8% a year, and pork, at 2.3%, while demand for
beef will rise by 2%, says the report on the
agricultural outlook for the next ten years. Brazil will
account for 63% of meat exports from non-OECD
member countries, and a third of total exports.
The new report calculates that cattle farming is
responsible for 80% of all greenhouse gas emissions
in the agricultural sector because of deforestation,
the use of fuels in burning, intestinal fermentation and
manure management. The FAO and OECD forecast
that the biggest increases in agricultural emissions
will come from Latin America, Asia and
Africa.Information provided by Valor Econômico.
Leather exports up almost 80% by
May
Brazil’s leather exports totaled US$714 million in the
first five months of this year, up 79% year on year,
according to the Center of Tanneries in Brazil (CICB),
based on data from the Foreign Trade Office.The
president of the CICB, Wolfgang Goerlich, estimates
monthly exports at between US$140 million and
US$150 million by the end of this year, allowing for
the fall in prices caused by the crisis in Europe. The
crisis hit May’s exports for the sector, when revenue
totaled US$158 million, down 1% year on year. This
would make 2010’s total revenue around US$1.75
billion, 51% up on 2009, when Brazil exported
US$1.16 billion, but 7% below 2008’s US$1.88.
Information provided by Centro das Indústrias de
Curtumes do Brasil (CICB).
POULTRY and PORK
Domestic Market Overview
Brazilian chicken market focuses on Asia
Brazilian chicken and pig farmers are adapting ever
more to the Asian markets. In the first five months of
this year Russia and Taiwan were the main buyers of
Brazilian pork. Of the 217,800 tons shipped in the
period, 102,700 were exported to Russia and 39,200
to Taiwan. And now Brazil is getting ready to enter
other important markets in the region. According to
the president of the Brazilian Association of Pork
Producers and Exporters (Abipecs), Pedro de
Camargo Neto, Brazil will comply with sanitary
requirements in Japan, China and South Korea next
year. With the increased competitiveness of Brazilian
production the possibility has opened up of getting
into a market so far dominated by the USA.
The latest USDA report says that US pork production
estimates for 2010 have been revised downwards
from 22.3 million to 22.1 million pounds because of
reduced export forecasts, from 4.4 million to 4.2
million pounds. The forecast for 2011 has been
maintained, at production of 22.7 million pounds and
exports of 4.55 million pounds. Per capita
consumption in the US will fall from 50.1 pounds in
2009 to 46.8 pounds in 2010 and 47.3 pounds in
2011.Chicken consumption is growing strongly in the
US, partly making up for reduced sales to strategic
markets. Even though per capita consumption has
been revised downwards in both 2010 and 2011, it
will remain the leading protein in the USA. Domestic
consumption will increase from 79.6 pounds per
person in 2009 to 83.7 pounds in 2010 and 85.7 in
2011. US exports, which will fall sharply in 2010 (from
6.8 million to 5.8 million pounds) could recover
slightly next year (to around 6 million pounds).
In the first four months of this year US chicken
exports fell by 11.8%, mainly because of barriers put
up by Russia and China, which slashed imports by
83.6% and 82.5%, respectively. Mexico then became
the biggest importer from the USA, with 143,500 tons
in the period. In the same period last year Russia
bought 208,400 tons, China 134,300 and Mexico
121,400 tons. Avisite says that Brazilian exports to
these countries have not risen significantly. Brazil is,
however, consolidating its leadership of the global
Halal* chicken market. Recently, Iran stated its
intention to increase its imports of Brazilian chicken.
In 2009 Brazil exported 1.3 million tons of Halal
chicken.
Domestic market
The live chicken market saw reasonable levels of
business and stable prices last week. In São Paulo
State a lower volume was traded, as buyers sought
to avid stockpiling. Supply rose as integrated farmers
entered the market. In São Paulo live chicken prices
were stable, with reports of little trade. In Minas
Online and in Print • Online Archive
Brazilian Meat Monitor, June 18, 2010 8 © 2010 Informa UK Ltd.
Gerais State the low levels of supply saw prices
recover. In the south and center-west prices were
stable. In the northeast prices recovered as demand
rose. On the wholesale market chicken meat sales
were moderate.
Although the trade in live pigs remains firm in the
southeast, the supply of animals from the south,
mainly Paraná and Santa Catarina States, prevented
price rises. In the south low levels of pork exports,
caused by the fall of the dollar against the real and
competition with other meats, have brought down the
prices of animals for slaughter. In the center-west the
supply of live animals from Mato Grosso State was
channeled to Goiás and the southeast because
prices were better there. Overall, despite the cold
weather, which normally favors consumption, sales of
pork were moderate as beef and chicken prices have
fallen.

POULTRY and PORK
News Summary
South Korean and Japan are the
new markets for Brazilian pork
Brazil is getting ready to meet the sanitary standards
for pork to be exported to South Korea, Japan and
China next year, says Pedro de Camargo Neto,
president of the Brazilian Association of Pork
Producers and Exporters (Abipecs).
Neto did not want to be drawn on figures, but he did
say that the sector will sell more in the second half of
the year than the first half. Pork exports from Brazil in
May earned US$118 million, 15% up year on year.
Volume was 46,028 tons, 11% down in the period
because of a fall in sales to Russia, the leading
market.
Online and in Print • Online Archive
Brazilian Meat Monitor, June 18, 2010 10 © 2010 Informa UK Ltd.
Rogério Kerber, executive director of the Pork
Product Industry Association (Sips), believes Brazil
will not be able to sell to Japan because there are no
sanitary agreements between the two countries.
Irineu Wessler, president of the Brazilian Association
of Pig Farmers (ABCS), says the opportunity to sell to
the Asians opens up the prospect of competing with
the Americans, but he says the time now is good for
the domestic market.
Brazil produces an annual total of about 3.2 million
tons of pork – of which 600,000 tons are exported.
Brazil consumes 13 kg per capita of pork - 4 kg of
fresh meat and 9 kg of processed meat – while
Europe consumes an average of 45 kg per capita.
Information provided by Diário do Comércio Indústria
& Serviços.
The main markets for Brazil’s pork
Russia and Hong Kong led imports of pork from
Brazil in the first five months of this year, at 102,665
tons and 41,378 tons, respectively, according to the
Brazilian Association of Pork Producers and
Exporters (Abipecs).
In revenue these two countries also led the way, with
Russia accounting for US$281.297 million and Hong
Kong, US$80.868 million.The third-ranked buyer in
the period was Ukraine, with 15,982 tons, worth
US$40.241 million, followed by Argentina (13,395
tons, US$38.464 million) and Angola (12,588 tons,
US$28.345 million). Information provided by Abipecs.
Russia and China: Brazil will not
benefit from the chicken crisis
With the reduction in imports of chicken from the USA
by Russia and China in the first four months of 2010,
Brazil has also suffered a fall in its exports to both
countries, despite expectations to the contrary. So
say data from Brazil’s Foreign Trade Office (SECEX).
In the first four months of 2010 25,563 tons of
chicken were exported to Russia.
There was indeed a rise, but only of 1.33%.Exports to
Continental China and Hong Kong fell, from 152,839
tons in the first four months of 2009, to 144,292 tons
in the same period in 2010 – down 5.59%.
Combined, exports to the two countries fell by 4.61%.
Revenue rose by 19% in the period but this was the
result of price rises on the international market.
Information provided by Avisite.
More chicken to Iran
Iran has expressed its intention to import more
chicken from Brazil, expanding the list of Brazilian
companies licensed to export to it. The
announcement came at a meeting between the
executive president of the Brazilian Poultry Farming
Association (Ubabef), Francisco Turra, and the
president of the Iranian Halal Supervision Center in
Brazil, Mohammad Mahdi Ghorbanian. Brazil is now
the world’s largest exporter of Halal chicken, shipping
about 1.3 million tons a year. 10,000 tons were
exported to Iran in 2009, worth US$18 million. “We
have high expectations about the market for 2010,
considering that in the first four months of the year
7,500 tons of chicken were exported to Iran, worth
US$11 million”, said Turra. Information provided by
Safras.
FAO: poultry to supply a third of
meat produced in 2010
A third of the 286.4 million tons of meat to be
produced this year globally will come from poultry,
mainly chicken, says the FAO. Since 2000 poultry’s
share of total meat production has grown by over
42%, while total meat production has increased by
22.7%.
More than half the additional 53 million tons between
2000 and 2010 has come from poultry (28.2 million
tons) which has seen its total share of production rise
from 28.5% to 33.1%. Pork, beef and lamb have seen
their shares fall be 3.3%, 11.9% and 6.7%,
respectively, in the same period. Information provided
by Avisite.
Chicken consumption up 300% in
Brazil, says AgraFNP
Global per capita chicken consumption has rose from
about 2 kilos a year in 1970 to over 10.5 kilos in
2009, says the USDA. In Brazil, the world’s largest
chicken exporter, between 1983 and 2009 it rose by
over 300%, while beef consumption fell and the rise
in pork consumption was modest. “There are several
explanations, but price is the most important one.
Also, the production cycle is short for chicken, which
means quick changes can be made to supply,
preventing price collapses”, says José Vicente
Ferraz, the technical director at Agra FNP.
Ferraz adds that chicken’s healthier image and the
increased income of lower-earners have helped. The
difference in price between chicken and beef are
expected to increase as environmental and sanitary
standards are raised. Brazil will benefit further from
global growth in chicken consumption with more jobs
Daily Online News • Online Every Week • Online Archive
© 2010 Informa UK Ltd. 11 Brazilian Meat Monitor, June 18, 2010
and other benefits stemming from soy and corn
production.Information provided by Folha de S.Paulo.
Chicken exports in 2010 up on 2009
so far
Data from Brazil’s Foreign Trade Office (SECEX)
published at the end of last week indicate that thanks
to a 5.67% increase in May the volume of fresh
chicken exported in 2010 has so far exceeded that in
2009. The difference, however, is no more than 387
tons (0.03% up on the first five months of 2009). The
exports of chicken cuts rose by 0.07%, and whole
chicken rose by 1.88%. This means added-value
products have suffered – salted chicken is down
3.42%, and processed chicken is down 11.13%.
Revenue, however, is up – except for processed
products, in which it has fallen by 12.18%. But as the
gains in the rest of the items were significant –
21.45% in cuts, 17.86% for whole chicken, and
28.47% for salted chicken – the overall figure for the
year was significantly up – by 17.82%. Global
revenue, however, fell 6.38% on January to May
2008. Information provided by Avisite.
FEED News
Not even Conab can save corn shipments
The World Cup and the first game for Brazil last
Tuesday (June 15th) made trade on the financial and
agricultural markets sparse. In some markets corn
prices fell. Corn, supply of which has been abundant
in Brazil, had its volume boosted by the winter
harvest 2009/10. By June 14th producers had taken
in 6.2% of the planted area (5.165 million hectares),
compared with 1.4% (4.901 million hectares) in the
same period last year. In addition, the dry weather
has led to early harvesting. These factors led to
buyers opting for corn that is yet to be harvested
instead of that already on the market.
The penultimate auction held with a Product Shipping
Premium (PEP) by the National Supply Company
(Conab), on June 8th, also contributed to lower prices
for corn, as the volume traded was well below
expectations. However, there was an adjustment
made to the premiums by Conab. For Mato Grosso
State, where corn prices are lower, the premium
adjustments were more significant. In the west of the
State (Sapezal) the premium rose from R$4.62/bag
to R$5.64/bag and in the southeast (Campo Verde)
from R$2.64/bag to R$3.54/bag.The price paid for
corn in the ports of Santos and Paranaguá, where
most of the corn sold in auctions goes, was around
R$16.00/bag and R$16.50/bag, respectively, well
below the reference market of Campinas
($19.70/bag).
Domestic and international demand for soy meal has
had a positive impact on prices. In the port of
Paranaguá the price per ton has been around R$565.
According to AgraFNP, the expectation is that soy
meal production this harvest will be 8% higher than
last year, at 24.9 million tons. Exports will be 12.6
million tons, compared with 12.253 million in 2009. If
confirmed, this will be the highest volume since 2005.
In regard to soy oil, the consultancy forecasts that
domestic consumption will be about 5.0 million tons,
with about two million going to biodiesel production.
Exports will total around 1.2 million tons and final
Brazilian stocks will be fewer than 400,000 tons, 8%
of total use.
